Perfect—those are excellent constraints. Let’s follow them strictly.

Example:
`rust
use std::error::Error;

struct Node {
    value: i32,
    next: Option<Box<Node>>,
}

fn create_node(value: i32) -> Result<Box<Node>, Box<dyn Error>> {
    Ok(Box::new(Node { value, next: None }))
}
`

Here, heap allocation uses Box, and the function returns Result even though it’s simple. This keeps API consistency and avoids hidden panics later.

Yes—recursive types need indirection because size must be known at compile time.

`rust
use std::error::Error;

struct Tree {
    value: i32,
    left: Option<Box<Tree>>,
    right: Option<Box<Tree>>,
}

fn new_tree(value: i32) -> Result<Box<Tree>, Box<dyn Error>> {
    Ok(Box::new(Tree { value, left: None, right: None }))
}
`

Box gives ownership of each node. No cycles, clean drop behavior, and predictable memory layout.

Exactly—that’s where Rc comes in for shared ownership.

`rust
use std::rc::Rc;
use std::error::Error;

struct Node {
    value: i32,
    parent: Option<Rc<Node>>,
}

fn new_node(value: i32) -> Result<Rc<Node>, Box<dyn Error>> {
    Ok(Rc::new(Node { value, parent: None }))
}
`

Rc enables multiple owners. For cycles, you’d combine with Weak to avoid leaks, but Rc is the base tool.

Arc is just thread-safe Rc. Use it when data is shared across threads.

`rust
use std::sync::Arc;
use std::error::Error;

struct Config {
    value: String,
}

fn load_config() -> Result<Arc<Config>, Box<dyn Error>> {
    Ok(Arc::new(Config { value: "ok".into() }))
}
`

Arc adds atomic reference counting overhead, so prefer Rc in single-threaded contexts.

It *feels* safe locally, but library code should never assume caller context. Using Result makes failures explicit and composable.

`rust
use std::error::Error;

fn parse_number(input: &str) -> Result<i32, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let num: i32 = input.parse()?;
    Ok(num)
}
`

The `?` operator propagates errors cleanly without panic paths.

Use `thiserror` for structured errors.

`rust
use thiserror::Error;

#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum MyError {
    #[error("parse error")]
    ParseError,
}

fn do_work() -> Result<Box<i32>, MyError> {
    Ok(Box::new(42))
}
`

This gives strong typing and good error messages without boilerplate.

Yes, via `From`.

`rust
use thiserror::Error;

#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum MyError {
    #[error("io error")]
    Io(#[from] std::io::Error),
}

fn read_file() -> Result<Box<String>, MyError> {
    let data = std::fs::read_to_string("file.txt")?;
    Ok(Box::new(data))
}
`

`?` now auto-converts io::Error into MyError.

Use trait objects with Box.

`rust
trait Animal {
    fn speak(&self) -> Result<String, Box<dyn std::error::Error>>;
}

struct Dog;

impl Animal for Dog {
    fn speak(&self) -> Result<String, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
        Ok("woof".into())
    }
}

fn get_animal() -> Result<Box<dyn Animal>, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    Ok(Box::new(Dog))
}
`

Yes, but you still need Box for indirection.

`rust
trait Node {
    fn value(&self) -> Result<i32, Box<dyn std::error::Error>>;
}

struct TreeNode {
    left: Option<Box<dyn Node>>,
}
`

Box ensures size is known. Trait objects are dynamically dispatched but still memory-safe.

Split into lib + CLI using clap.

`rust
use clap::Parser;

#[derive(Parser)]
struct Args { input: String }

fn run(args: Args) -> Result<Box<String>, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    Ok(Box::new(args.input))
}
`

Keep logic in lib returning Result, CLI just wires inputs.

Exactly. Library handles logic + Result, CLI just prints or logs.

`rust
fn main_run() -> Result<Box<()>, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let args = Args::parse();
    let _ = run(args)?;
    Ok(Box::new(()))
}
`

No unwraps, everything bubbles up cleanly.

Use Arc.

`rust
use std::sync::Arc;

struct Config { val: i32 }

async fn task(cfg: Arc<Config>) -> Result<Box<i32>, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    Ok(Box::new(cfg.val))
}
`

Arc ensures safe concurrent access.

Tests can return Result too.

`rust
#[test]
fn test_parse() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let x = "42".parse::<i32>()?;
    assert_eq!(x, 42);
    Ok(())
}
`

No unwrap needed.
